{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488629"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:50:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:50:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"495"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/495"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.07,0.01,0.1,0.69]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"495"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52461"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/495"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"495"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37815"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1810"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7892"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8104"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15222"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52461"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine follow-up. His last review was two years ago. He reports possible weight loss and decreased appetite. He now gets up twice at night to void and his urine stream is not as strong as it used to be. He has a medical history of hypertension, eczema, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. His regular medications include hydrochlorothiazide and a tiotropium inhaler. He has a 25 pack-year smoking history and drinks about four glasses of wine most evenings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. His BMI is 29 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. His skin appears pale and some discoloration of his nails is noted (image). Chest examination reveals gynaecomastia, some spider naevi on his upper chest, and scattered wheezes on auscultation. The rest of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the nail appearances?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dietary deficiency","Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease","Eczema","Chronic kidney disease","Cirrhosis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe discoloration of nails in the image is known as leuconychia. This particular pattern of leuconychia can be referred to as Terry\u0027s nail. Given the patient\u0027s alcohol consumption and the presence of gynaecomastia and spider naevi, the most likely explanation is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecirrhosis\u003C/strong\u003E. In this case, the white discolouration appearing on nails is most likely caused by the hypoalbuminaemia of chronic liver disease. The nail beds become opaque, often leaving only a rim of pink nail bed at the top of the nail. The exact mechanism is uncertain - it may be due to compression of capillary flow by extracellular fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDietary deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E can cause leuconychia, but there is not significant evidence to label this patient as deficient, making it a less likely cause. While the patient reports decreased appetite, this alone is not sufficient to diagnose a dietary deficiency severe enough to cause nail changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic kidney disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a possible explanation for leuconychia, but his symptoms suggestive of bladder neck obstruction are not strong pointers towards this being a likely cause. Additionally, there are no other clinical signs or symptoms indicative of chronic kidney disease in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEczema\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with leuconychia. While the patient has a history of eczema, this skin condition primarily affects the epidermis and does not usually cause changes to the nail bed or matrix.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic obstructive pulmonary disease\u003C/strong\u003E (COPD) is not known to cause leuconychia. While the patient has a history of COPD and smoking, these factors do not directly affect nail appearance in the manner shown in the image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that leuconychia is not unique to liver disease and can also occur with renal failure, fungal infections, minor trauma, lymphoma, or can be congenital. However, in this clinical context, with the patient\u0027s history of alcohol consumption and other physical findings suggestive of liver disease (gynaecomastia and spider naevi), cirrhosis is the most likely explanation for the nail appearances.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Leuconychia is present in about 50% of patients with chronic liver disease, but it is a non-specific physical sign also seen in conditions such as diabetes and congestive heart failure.","Cirrhosis can present with subtle signs such as leuconychia, gynaecomastia, and spider naevi, even before overt liver failure symptoms appear.","A thorough physical examination is crucial in patients with a history of alcohol misuse to detect early signs of cirrhosis."],"references":["Pitukweerakul S, Pilla S. Terry\u0027s Nails and Lindsay\u0027s Nails: Two Nail Abnormalities in Chronic Systemic Diseases. J Gen Intern Med. 2016;31(8):970. doi:10.1007/s11606-016-3628-z. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4945547/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37815"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"495"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19037"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19037"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/82d40f72-48d9-4cfd-9921-dddeefec0f78.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/82d40f72-48d9-4cfd-9921-dddeefec0f78.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":430}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37815"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-05T15:17:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-05T15:17:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"495"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52461"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda